I can only do a Covid test with help from my partner or the app

2 years in, when testing is crucial

We can‚Äôt‚Ä¶
I've said it before and I'll say it again: life is too short for bad coffee.
RT @MattChorley: Easily the best thing I‚Äôve read on this case. A must read for both sides in the culture war (and the rest of us in the mid‚Ä¶

The UKHSA said new developments have been made, including "the use of remote live video assistance", expected to come over the next few weeks.

But it suggested people with total sight loss may still require help from others - indicating the issue is not going away anytime soon.

I also heard from the people behind the amazing @BeMyEyes app, which connects blind and partially sighted people with sighted volunteers who help with daily tasks via a live chat, and has been really useful for many struggling to take and read back Covid tests.

I also interviewed someone from the @RNIB, who told me about the charity's work towards improving both PCR and lateral flow tests for blind and partially sighted people. 

Lots of improvements have been made, but they said accessibility needs to be "tackled right from the start"

I spoke to content creator @lucyedwards, who called "the whole process completely inaccessible".

There are some two million people in the UK with sight loss. They need to be able to do a test independently without putting others at risk of catching the virus.

For most of us, doing a Covid test requires little thought - but for blind and partially sighted people, it's still a challenge. Yes, two years into the pandemic.
